              <li><p>Along <m>x=0</m>, the limit is:
                  <me>
                    \lim_{(x,y)\to(0,0)} \frac{\sin(x^2)}{y} =  \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\sin(x^2)}{x^2}.
                  </me>
                  This can be evaluated with L'H&#xf4;pital's Rule or from known limits; it is 1.</p></li>
            </ol>

            <p>Since the limits along the lines <m>y=mx</m> are not the same as the limit along <m>y=x^2</m>, the overall limit does not exist.</p>
