          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\lim\limits_{(x,y)\to(1,2)} \frac{x+y-3}{x^2-1}</m></p>

            <ol>
              <li><p>Along the path <m>y=2</m>.</p></li>

              <li><p>Along the path <m>y=x+1</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol>
              <li><p>Along <m>y=2</m>, the limit is:
                  <md>
                    <mrow>\lim_{(x,y)\to(1,2)} \frac{x+y-3}{x^2-1} \amp  =  \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{x-1}{x^2-1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{1}{x+1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 1/2.</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p></li>

              <li><p>Along <m>y=x+1</m>, the limit is:
                  <md>
                    <mrow>\lim_{(x,y)\to(1,2)} \frac{x+y-3}{x^2-1} \amp  =  \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{2(x-1)}{x^2-1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{2}{x+1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 1.</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p></li>
            </ol>

            <p>Since the limits along the lines <m>y=2</m> and <m>y=x+1</m> differ, the overall limit does not exist.</p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
