      <exercise>
        <webwork seed="1">
          <setup>
            <var name="">
              <static></static>
            </var>
            <pg-code>
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\lim\limits_{(x,y)\to(\pi,\pi/2)} \frac{\sin(x) }{\cos(y) }</m></p>

            <ol>
              <li><p>Along the path <m>x=\pi</m>.</p></li>

              <li><p>Along the path <m>y=x-\pi/2</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol>
              <li><p>Along <m>x=\pi</m>, the limit is:
                  <md>
                    <mrow>\lim_{(x,y)\to(\pi,\pi/2)} \frac{\sin(x) }{\cos(y) } \amp  =  \lim_{y\to \pi/2} \frac{0}{\cos(y) }</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 0.</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p></li>

              <li><p>Along <m>y=x-\pi/2</m>, the limit is:
                  <md>
                    <mrow>\lim_{(x,y)\to(\pi,\pi/2)} \frac{\sin(x) }{\cos(y) } \amp  =  \lim_{x\to \pi} \frac{\sin(x) }{\cos(x-\pi/2)}</mrow>
                    <intertext>Apply L'H\^opital's Rule:</intertext>
                    <mrow>\amp = \lim_{x\to \pi} \frac{\cos(x) }{\sin(x-\pi/2)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = -1.</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p></li>
            </ol>

            <p>Since the limits along the lines <m>x=\pi</m> and <m>y=x-\pi</m> differ, the overall limit does not exist.</p>
          </solution>
